03858nam a22005415i 9780520940840DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20042004cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209408407 a10.1525/97805209408402doi  a(DE-B1597)520103  a(OCoLC)808600726  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aML1700b.K715 2007 7aMUS0280002bisacsh04a782.10922432221 aKramer, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOpera and Modern Culture :bWagner and Strauss /cLawrence Kramer. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPrologue -- t1. Opera -- t2. Contesting Wagner -- t3. The Waters of Prometheus -- t4. Enchantment and Modernity -- t5. Modernity's Cutting Edge -- t6. Video as Jugendstil -- t7. Fin-de-Siècle Fantasies -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this enlightening and entertaining book, one of the most original and sophisticated musicologists writing today turns his attention to music's most dramatic genre. Extending his ongoing project of clarifying music's various roles in Western society, Kramer brings to opera his distinctive and pioneering blend of historical concreteness and theoretical awareness. Opera is legendary for going to extremes, a tendency that has earned it a reputation for unreality. Opera and Modern Culture shows the reverse to be true. Kramer argues that for the past two centuries the preoccupation of a group of famous operas with the limits of supremacy and debasement helped to define a normality that seems the very opposite of the operatic. Exemplified in a series of beloved examples, a certain idea of opera-a fiction of opera-has contributed in key ways to the modern era's characterizations of desire, identity, and social order. Opera and Modern Culture exposes this process at work in operas by Richard Wagner, who put modernity on the agenda in ways no one after him could ignore, and by the young Richard Strauss. The book continues the initiative of much recent writing in treating opera as a multimedia rather than a primarily musical form. From Lohengrin and The Ring of the Niebelung to Salome and Elektra, it traces the rich interplay of operatic visions and voices and their contexts in the birth pangs of modern life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMusicxPhilosophy and aesthetics. 0aOperaxSocial aspects. 0aSex in opera. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Opera.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940840423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520940840.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles